Hi guys,

We have this API now:

``` javascript
var Comp = React.createClass({
  onSubmit: function (data, resetForm, invalidateForm) {
     myAjaxService('/url', data)
      .error(function (errors) {
        errors // { test: "Not valid input says the server" }
        invalidateForm(errors);
      }); 
  }, 
  render: function () {
    return (
      <Formsy.Form onSubmit={this.onSubmit}>
        <MyInput name="test"/>
      </Formsy.Form>
    );
  }
});
```

You could basically do whatever you want when server responds, but to map to inputs you use the "invalidateForm" callback.

Does that solve it? Maybe the documentation is lacking a bit here?

Btw, how do you feel about just mapping the inputs to whatever you want instead? To me it does feel a bit weird to declare data structure in the "HTML" of the component. An example could be:

``` javascript
var mapModel = function (model) {
  return {
    "startYear": model.startYear,
    "endYear": model.endYear,
    "terms": [
      {
        "name": "term1",
        "startDate": model.term1_startDate
        "endDate": model.term1_endDate
      }
      {
        "name": "term2",
        "startDate": model.term2_startDate
        "endDate": model.term2_endDate
      }
    ]
  };
};
<Formsy.Form mapModel={mapModel}/>
```

This gives a lot more freedom and it reduces code complexity a lot. It also prevents locking an "HTML"-definition into a certain data structure. What do you think?

Hi @burtyish,

Actually, the input itself does not need a name attribute. Create your own credit card info formsy element, something like:

``` javascript
var CreditCardInfoInput = React.createClass({
  mixins: [Formsy.Mixin],
  updateValue: function (event) {
    this.setValue(event.target.value);
  },
  render: function () {
    return <input value={this.getValue()} onChange={this.updateValue}/>
  }
});
```

This wraps your plain input, without a name attribute, into a formsy element. You can now use it like this:

``` javascript
<Formsy.Form>
  <CreditCardInfoInput name="creditcardinfo"/>
</Formsy.Form>
```

The name attribute used here has nothing to do with the input inside. It is just a property on the **CreditCardInfoInput** component that Formsy will use to identify the property name for the value. So you are following the guidelines with this solution.

Hope this was an okay explanation, but please let me know if you have more questions :-)

Hm, it is not fixed, broke all the tests.

It creates a circular reaction where the change of that value requires a new validation which again sets the value and again validates and so on.

Actually I think you have to structure this a bit differently. Instead of using the "defaultValue" on the input I would do this:

``` javascript
  componentWillReceiveProps: function (nextProps) {

   // Only change to the new default value if it is currently showing the old one
    if (this.getValue() === this.props.defaultValue && nextProps.defaultValue !== this.props.defaultValue) {
      this.setValue(nextProps.defaultValue);
    }
  },
```

And if you want an empty input to change into the default input:

``` javascript
  changeValue: function (event) {
    this.setValue(event.target.value || this.props.defaultValue);
  }
```

I think this will solve your problem :-)

Hi there!

Formsy.Forms require Formsy elements, you are using a native input. If you wrap those inputs in components:

``` javascript
var MyInput = React.createClass({
  mixins: [Formsy.Mixin],
  changeValue: function (event) {
    this.setValue(event.target.value);
  },
  render: function () {
    return <input value={this.getValue()} onChange={this.changeValue}/>
  }
});

// In form component
<Formsy.Form>
  <MyInpuit name="email"/>
</Formsy.Form>

```

Maybe I should document this a bit better? The reason it works this way is that creating formsy element components, like `MyInput`, is what gives you all the functionality. It has been suggested to give a default input out of the box, but it is so rarely you actually need just a simple input. You probably always want to wrap some divs, show your validation errors as you see fit etc.

This almost works. The problem is that the defaultValue (value?) doesn't get loaded on first page load. For example, this code block:

``` jsx
'use strict';

var React = require('react');
var Formsy = require('formsy-react');

var Input = React.createClass({
    mixins: [Formsy.Mixin],
    changeValue: function(event) {
        this.setValue(event.currentTarget.value || this.props.defaultValue);
    },
    componentWillReceiveProps: function (nextProps) {
        // Only change to the new default value if it is currently showing the old one
        if (this.getValue() === this.props.defaultValue && nextProps.defaultValue !== this.props.defaultValue) {
            this.setValue(nextProps.defaultValue);
        }
    },
    render: function() {
        var className = this.showRequired() ? 'required' : this.showError() ? 'error' : null;
        var errorMessage = this.getErrorMessage();

        return (
            <div className={className}>
                <input type="text" value={this.getValue()} onChange={this.changeValue} />
            </div>
        );
    }
});

module.exports = Input;

```

and this component...

``` jsx
<Formsy.Form url="/users" onSuccess={this.changeUrl} onValid={this.enableButton} onInvalid={this.disableButton}>
  <Form.Input name="firstName" required defaultValue={this.state.profile.first}/>
  <button type="submit" disabled={!this.state.canSubmit}>Submit</button>
</Formsy.Form>
```

Will load an input element with an empty value. However, by entering value AND THEN deleting it will the defaultValue appear in the input. Here's a .gif:

![out](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/6847633/5991027/0871470a-a987-11e4-833f-993719aab4fb.gif)

I think the reason for this behavior might be because `nextProps.defaultValue` is undefined on the first  load. I guess it's because `componentWillReceiveProps` is not called on the initial render. Any suggestions on what to do here?

Let me know if I misunderstand, but you want the input to show "John" instantly?

I think the easiest way to achieve this is by also passing it as a value:

``` javascript
<Formsy.Form url="/users" onSuccess={this.changeUrl} onValid={this.enableButton} onInvalid={this.disableButton}>
  <Form.Input name="firstName" required value={this.state.profile.first} defaultValue={this.state.profile.first}/>
  <button type="submit" disabled={!this.state.canSubmit}>Submit</button>
</Formsy.Form>
```

So you handle the "initial value" using the normal "value" attribute, and your custom "defaultValue" attribute as the fallback value. You could consider also using the "componentWillMount" method to grab the "defaultValue" prop and set the value of the input:

``` javascript
var Input = React.createClass({
    mixins: [Formsy.Mixin],
    componentWillMount: function () {
      this.setValue(this.props.defaultValue);
    },
    changeValue: function(event) {
        this.setValue(event.currentTarget.value || this.props.defaultValue);
    },
    componentWillReceiveProps: function (nextProps) {
        // Only change to the new default value if it is currently showing the old one
        if (this.getValue() === this.props.defaultValue && nextProps.defaultValue !== this.props.defaultValue) {
            this.setValue(nextProps.defaultValue);
        }
    },
    render: function() {
        var className = this.showRequired() ? 'required' : this.showError() ? 'error' : null;
        var errorMessage = this.getErrorMessage();

        return (
            <div className={className}>
                <input type="text" value={this.getValue()} onChange={this.changeValue} />
            </div>
        );
    }
});
```

Then you do not have to pass the "value" attribute at all, as the "defaultValue" attribute will be the initial value of the input.

