Hm, I have been thinking a bit more on this. Like a plain input you might want to pass the changes through your application state store. Typically `onChange` on an input and `value={this.state.value}`. With Formsy, in combination with f.ex. Cerebral:

``` js
@Cerebral({
  form: ['form']
})
class MyForm extends React.Component {
  onFormChange(data) {
    this.props.signals.formChanged({form: data});
  }
  render() {
    return (
      <Formsy.Form onChange={(data) => this.onFormChange(data)}>
        <MyInput name="foo" value={this.props.form.foo}/>
      </Formsy.Form>
    );
  }
}
```

This is a typical setup for creating "application state". The problem with implementing what is suggested here is that the value prop will change on every change of the form. So it will always be a pristine value.

This is the difficult balance of internal/external state handling. I think it is important to let developers control the form from some external state store, without messing up the pristine stuff. Maybe we should rather have a `pristineValue` or `defaultValue`? That way you can control it however you like?

